Tan Shaun Tan's Gallery] with biography and artbooks on Inside Your ART\n\n{{World Fantasy Award Best Artist}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Children's literature|Visual arts|Animation|Australia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tan, Shaun}}\n[[Category:Australian children's writers]]\n[[Category:Australian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Australian speculative fiction artists]]\n[[Category:Australian children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:World Fantasy Award-winning artists]]\n[[Category:Astrid Lindgren Memorial Award winners]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:University of Western Australia alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Fremantle]]\n[[Category:People from Perth, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Artists from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Directors of Best Animated Short Academy Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}}{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox comics creator\n|image = Shaun Tan 2011-05-22 002.jpg\n| caption = Shaun Tan in 2011\n| alt           = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1974}}\n| birth_place   = [[Fremantle]], Western Australia\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = Australian\n| spouse     = Rick Astley\n| children    =\n| area          = \n| cartoonist    =\n| write         = y\n| art           = y\n| pencil        = y\n| ink           = \n| edit          = \n| publish       = \n| letter        = \n| color         = \n| alias         = \n| signature     =\n| signature_alt = \n| notable works = ''[[The Red Tree (Shaun Tan)|The Red Tree]]''<br />''[[The Lost Thing]]''<br />''[[The Arrival (graphic novel) |The Arrival]]''\n| awards        =\n| website       = [http://www.shauntan.net/ shauntan.net]<br />[http://thebirdking.blogspot.com.au/ thebirdking.blogspot.com.au]\n| subcat        = Australian}}\n'''Shaun Tan''' (born 1974) is an Australian artist, writer and film maker. He won an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for ''[[The Lost Thing]]'', a 2011 animated film adaptation of a 2000 picture book he wrote and illustrated. Other books he has written and illustrated include ''[[The Red Tree (Shaun Tan)|The Red Tree]]'' and ''[[The Arrival (graphic novel)|The Arrival]]''.\n\nTan was born in [[Fremantle]], Western Australia, and grew up in the northern suburbs of [[Perth]], Western Australia. In 2006, his wordless [[graphic novel]] ''The Arrival'' won the Book of the Year prize as part of the [[New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards]].<ref>{{Citation|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald| url = http://www.smh.com.au/news/books/2007-nsw-premiers-literary-awards/2007/05/29/1180205249745.html | title = 2007 NSW Premier's Literary Awards | date = 30 May 2007}}</ref> The same book won the [[Children's Book Council of Australia]] [[Children's Book of the Year Award: Picture Book|Picture Book of the Year]] award in 2007.<ref>{{Citation | contribution-url = http://cbc.org.au/winner07.htm | publisher = CBCA | title = Book of the Year Awards | contribution = Winners 2007}}.</ref> and the [[Western Australian Premier's Book Awards]] Premier's Prize in 2006.<ref>{{Citation | contribution = Shaun Tan | contribution-url = http://pba.slwa.wa.gov.au/hall_of_fame/shaun_tan | title = Premier's Book Awards Hall of Fame | publisher = [[State Library of Western Australia]]}}.</ref>\n\nTan's work has been described as an \"Australian vernacular\" that is \"at once banal and uncanny, familiar and strange, local and universal, reassuring and scary, intimate and remote, [[Street children|guttersnipe]] and [[sprezzatura]]. No rhetoric, no straining for effect. Never other than itself.\"<ref name = Robb>{{cite web|last= Robb|first= Peter | title = The view from outside|url= http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/art-and-design/the-view-from-outside-20130909-2tes9.html | work = The Sydney Morning Herald | accessdate = 16 September 2013|date= 13 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nFor his career contribution to \"children's and young adult literature in the broadest sense\" Tan won the 2011 [[Astrid Lindgren Memorial Award]] from the Swedish Arts Council, the biggest prize in children's literature.<ref name =alma2011 />\n\n== Biography ==\n\n===Early life===\nAs a boy, Tan spent time illustrating poems and stories and drawing dinosaurs, robots and spaceships. At school he was known as a talented artist.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography: Shaun Tan|url=http://www.scholastic.com/teachers/contributor/shaun-tan|publisher=Scholastic|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> At the age of eleven, he became a fan of ''[[The Twilight Zone]]'' television series as well as books that bore similar themes. Tan cites [[Ray Bradbury]] as a favorite at this time. These stories led to Tan writing his own short stories. Of his effort at writing as a youth, Tan tells, \"I have a small pile of rejection letters as testament to this ambition!\"<ref name=\"locusmag\">{{cite journal |title=Shaun Tan: Out of Context |first=Karen |last=Haber |journal=Locus |issue=12 |date=December 2001 |url=http://www.locusmag.com/2001/Issue12/Tan.html |accessdate=2007-07-25}}</ref> At the age of sixteen, Tan's first illustration appeared in the Australian magazine ''[[Aurealis]]'' in 1990.<ref name=\"locusmag\" />\n\n===Transition to illustration===\nTan almost studied to become a geneticist, and enjoyed chemistry, physics, history and English while in high school as well as art and claimed that he did not really know what he wanted to do.<ref name= \"locusmag\" /> During his university studies, Tan decided to move from academic studies to working as an artist.<ref name=\"hsc\">{{Citation | title = Visual arts requirements case studies | contribution = Shaun Tan | contribution-url = http://hsc.csu.edu.au/visual_arts/requirements/case_studies/illustrator_graphic_designer/122232ShaTanCDoc5.html | publisher = NSW HSC Online}}.</ref>\n\nTan continued his education at the [[University of Western Australia]] where he studied Fine Arts, English Literature and History. While this was of interest to him, there was little practical work involved.<ref name =\"hsc\" /> In 1995, he graduated with a Bachelor of Arts.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.austlit.edu.au/run?ex=ShowAgent&agentId=A%2C%7D9 | publisher = AustLit | title = Agent}}.</ref>\n\n===Work process===\nInitially, Tan works in black and white because the final reproductions would be printed that way. Some black and white mediums he uses include pens, inks, acrylics, charcoal, scraperboard, photocopies, and linocuts.<ref name=\"locusmag\" /> Tan's current colour works still begin in black and white. He uses a graphite pencil to make sketches on ordinary copy paper. The sketches are then reproduced numerous times with different versions varying with parts added or removed. Sometimes scissors are used for this purpose. The cut and paste [[collage]] idea in these early stages is often extend to the finished production with many of his illustrations using such materials as \"glass, metal, cuttings from other books and dead insects\".<ref name=\"locusmag\" />\n\nTan describes himself as a slow worker who revises his work many times along the way. He is interested in loss and alienation, and believes that children in particular react well to issues of natural justice. He feels he is \"like a translator\" of ideas, and is happy and flattered to see his work adapted and interpreted in film and music (such as by the [[Australian Chamber Orchestra]]).<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/bookshow/stories/2008/2258905.htm|title=Shaun Tan: ''Tales from Outer Suburbia''|publisher=[[ABC Radio National]]|work=[[The Book Show]]|date=29 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Influences===\nTan draws from a large source of inspiration and cites many influences on his work. His comment on the subject is: \"I\u2019m pretty omnivorous when it comes to influences, and I like to admit this openly.\"<ref name = \"locusmag\" /> Some influences are very direct. ''[[The Lost Thing]]'' is a strong example where Tan makes visual references to famous artworks. Many of his influences are a lot more subtle visually, some of the influences are ideological. Below are some influences he has named in various interviews:\n\n*Films: ''[[Brazil (1985 film) |Brazil]]'', ''[[Yellow Submarine (film)|Yellow Submarine]]''\n*Filmmakers: [[Tim Burton]], [[Terry Gilliam]], [[Stanley Kubrick]], [[Ridley Scott]]\n*Artists and illustrators: [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]], [[Hieronymus Bosch]], [[Raymond Briggs]], Ron Brooks, Frederic Clement, [[Joseph Cornell]], [[Giorgio de Chirico]], [[Milton Glaser]], [[Edward Gorey]], [[John Olsen (Australian artist)|John Olsen]], [[Michael Leunig]], [[Ren\u00e9 Magritte]], [[Sidney Nolan]], [[Gerald Scarfe]], [[Katsushika Hokusai]], [[J. Otto Seibold]], [[Peter S\u00eds]], [[Lane Smith (illustrator)|Lane Smith]], [[Ralph Steadman]], [[Arthur Streeton]], [[Brett Whiteley]], [[John Brack]], [[Fred Williams]], and [[Chris Van Allsburg]]\n*Other: paintings in galleries, \"an arrangement of clouds, a lighting effect, a picture in a newspaper, or indeed supermarket plumbing\",<ref>{{Citation | publisher = [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] | url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/arts/articulate/200705/s1937072.htm | date = May 2005 | title = Shaun Tan: Solving the puzzle | access-date = 13 October 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080725163628/http://www.abc.net.au/news/arts/articulate/200705/s1937072.htm | archive-date = 25 July 2008 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}.</ref> incidents, textures and accidental compositions created by objects, things from other cultures and times, Polish poster art, streets, clouds, jokes, times of the day, people, animals, the way paint runs down a canvas, or colors go together.\n\n===Patronage===\nThe Shaun Tan Award for Young Artists is sponsored by the [[City of Subiaco]] and open to all Perth school children between 5 and 17 years. The award is aimed at encouraging creativity in two-dimensional works. It is held annually with award winners announced in May and finalists' works exhibited at the Subiaco Library throughout June.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://esvc000818.wic015u.server-web.com/cos/events%5Cshauntan.html | title = Shaun Tan Award for Young Artists }}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n;1992: [[Writers of the Future#Illustrators_of_the_Future|L. Ron Hubbard Illustrators of the Future Contest]]: First Australian to win<ref name= \"locusmag\" />\n;1993: [[Ditmar Award results|Ditmar Award]], Artwork, Nominated for ''Relics''<ref name = sfadb>{{Cite web |url = http://www.sfadb.com/Shaun_Tan |title = Science fiction awards database}}</ref>\n;1995: Ditmar Award, Professional Artwork, Winner for ''[[Aurealis]]'' and ''[[Eidolon Publications#Eidolon magazine |Eidolon]]''<ref name=\"locusmag\" />\n;1996: Ditmar Award, Artwork, Winner for [[Eidolon Publications#Eidolon magazine|Eidolon]] Issue 19 (Cover)<ref name=sfadb />\n;1997: Ditmar Award, Professional Artwork, Nominated for artwork in [[Eidolon Publications#Eidolon magazine | Eidolon]] and the cover of ''The Stray Cat''<ref name=sfadb />\n;1998: [[Crichton Award_for_Children's_Book Illustration |Crichton Award]], Winner for ''The Viewer''\n: [[Children's Book Council of Australia]], Notable Book for ''The Viewer''\n: Ditmar Award, Artwork/Artist, Nominated for ''The Viewer''<ref name=sfadb />\n: [[Western Australian Premier's Book Awards]], Children's Book, Shortlisted for ''The Playground''\n;1999: ''Aurealis'' Conveners' Award for Excellence for ''The Rabbits''\n: [[Children's Book Council of Australia]], Notable Book for ''The Playground''\n: Children's Book Council of Australia, Picture Book of the Year, Winner for ''The Rabbits''\n: Ditmar Award, Australian Professional Artwork, Nominated for ''The Rabbits''<ref name =sfadb />\n: Spectrum Gold Award for Book Illustration for ''The Rabbits''\n;2000: APA Design Award for ''Memorial''\n: Children's Book Council of Australia, Picture Book of the Year, Honour Book for ''Memorial''\n: Ditmar Award, Artwork, Winner for ''The Coode St Review Of Science Fiction''<ref name=sfadb />\n: Spectrum Gold Award for Book Illustration\n: [[Western Australian Premier's Book Awards]], Writing for Young Adults award, Shortlisted for ''Lost Thing''<ref name = \"pbk00\">{{cite web |title=Western Australian Premier's Book Awards \u2013 2000 Shortlist | publisher =State Library of Western Australia | url= http://www.liswa.wa.gov.au/pbk00shlst.html}}</ref>\n;2001: Ditmar Award, Artwork, Winner for ''[[The Lost Thing]]''<ref name =sfadb />\n: Children's Book Council of Australia, Picture Book of the Year, Honour Book for ''The Lost Thing''\n: [[Western Australian Premier's Book Awards]], Children's Books, Shortlisted for ''Red Tree''\n: [[World Fantasy Award for Best Artist]]<ref name =\"World Fantasy Convention 2010\" />\n;2002: Children's Book Council of Australia, Picture Book of the Year, Honour Book for ''The Red Tree''\n: [[New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards#Patricia Wrightson Prize for Children's Literature | New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards, Patricia Wrightson Prize for Children's Literature]] Winner for ''Red Tree''\n;2006: Premier's Prize and Children's Books category winner in the Western Australian Premier's Book Awards for ''[[The Arrival (graphic novel)|The Arrival]]''\n;2007: [[Ditmar Award results|Ditmar Award]], Artwork, Nominated for ''The Arrival''<ref name =sfadb />\n: [[Children's Book Council of Australia]], Picture Book of the Year, Honour Book for ''The Lost Thing''\n: [[World Fantasy Award for Best Artist]]<ref>{{Citation | date = November 2007 | url = http://www.locusmag.com/2007/11_WfaWinners.html | newspaper = Locus Online News | title = World Fantasy Awards Winners}}.</ref>\n: [[New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards#Community Relations Commission Award | New South Wales Premier's Literary Awards, Community Relations Commission Award]] for ''The Arrival''\n: Children's Book Council of Australia, Picture Book of the Year for 'The Arrival'.\n;2008: [[Angoul\u00eame International Comics Festival Prize for Best Comic Book]] for ''L\u00e0 o\u00f9 vont nos p\u00e8res'', the French edition of ''The Arrival''<ref>{{cite web | trans-title = Official 2008 Fauve D'Or trophy: Best album prize | url = http://www.bdangouleme.com/49-palmares-2008-fauve-dor-prix-du-meilleur-album | title = Palmar\u00e8s Officiel 2008 Fauve D'Or: Prix du Meilleur Album | work = Festival International de la Bande Dessin\u00e9e d'Angoul\u00eame | language = French | accessdate = 2008-01-27 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080128233259/http://www.bdangouleme.com/49-palmares-2008-fauve-dor-prix-du-meilleur-album | archivedate = 28 January 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n: [[Hugo Award]], Nominated for Best Related Book for ''The Arrival''<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web | publisher = Denvention | url = http://www.denvention.org/hugos/08hugonomlist.php | title = 2008 Hugo Award Nomination list | accessdate = 2008-03-29 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081221004127/http://www.denvention.org/hugos/08hugonomlist.php | archivedate = 21 December 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n: [[Hugo Award]], Nominated for Best Professional Artist (also in 2009 and 2010)\n: Western Australian Premier's Book Awards Young Adult category winner for ''Tales from Outer Suburbia''\n: [[Boston Globe-Horn Book Award]], Special Citation for ''The Arrival''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hbook.com/2011/05/news/boston-globe-horn-book-awards/past-boston-globe-horn-book-award-winners|title=Past Boston Globe \u2013 Horn Book Award Winners \u2013 The Horn Book|website=www.hbook.com|access-date=2016-04-21}}</ref>\n;2009: Ditmar Award, Artwork, Winner for ''Tales from Outer Suburbia''<ref name=sfadb />\n: Children's Book Council of Australia, Picture Book of the Year, Honour Book for ''The Lost Thing''\n: [[World Fantasy Award for Best Artist]]<ref name =\"World Fantasy Convention 2010\">{{cite web | publisher =World Fantasy Convention | year = 2010| title = Award Winners and Nominees | url= http://www.worldfantasy.org/awards/awardslist.html/ |accessdate= 4 Feb 2011}}</ref>\n;2010: [[Adelaide Festival Awards for Literature]], winner of the Children's Literature Award category and the South Australian Premier's Award for ''Tales from Outer Suburbia''\n: [[Dromkeen Medal]]\n: [[Hugo Award]], [[Hugo Award for Best Professional Artist |Best Professional Artist]]\n;2011: [[Academy Award]], Won [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film|Best Short Film (Animated)]] for ''The Lost Thing''\n: [[Astrid Lindgren Memorial Award]]<ref name=alma2011>[http://www.alma.se/en/Award-winners/2011-Recipient/ \"2011: Shaun Tan: A masterly visual storyteller\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115172909/http://www.alma.se/en/Award-winners/2011-Recipient/ |date=15 January 2013 }}. The Astrid Lindgren Memorial Award. Retrieved 2012-08-13.</ref>\n: Ditmar Award, Artwork, Winner for ''The Lost Thing''<ref name =sfadb />\n: Ditmar Award, Artwork, Nominated for ''Australis Imaginarium''<ref name=sfadb />\n: [[Hugo Award]], [[Hugo Award for Best Professional Artist |Best Professional Artist]]<ref>{{cite web|title= 2011 Hugo Award Winners |url= http://www.thehugoawards.org/2011/08/2011-hugo-award-winners/ |publisher=The Hugo Awards | accessdate =27 August 2014}}</ref>\n: [[Peter Pan Prize]] for the [[Swedish language |Swedish]] translation of ''The Arrival''<ref>{{cite web|title= Tidigare mottagare | work = Peter Pan-priset|url = http://ibby.se/priserutmarkelser/peter-pan-priset/tidigare-pristagare/ | language = sv | publisher = [[International Board on Books for Young People]] | accessdate= 27 August 2014}}</ref>\n;2014: [[Locus Award]], Artist<ref name=sfadb />\n: [[Ditmar Award results|Ditmar Award]], Artwork, Winner for ''Rules of Summer''<ref name =sfadb />\n: Boston Globe-Horn Book Award, Picture Book Honor for ''Rules of Summer''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hbook.com/2011/05/news/boston-globe-horn-book-awards/past-boston-globe-horn-book-award-winners|title=Past Boston Globe \u2013 Horn Book Award Winners \u2013 The Horn Book|website=www.hbook.com|access-date=2016-04-21}}</ref>\n;2019: [[World Fantasy Award for Best Artist]], Finalist<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldfantasy.org/world-fantasy-awards%e2%84%a0-2019/|title=World Fantasy Awards\u2120 2019 {{!}} World Fantasy Convention|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>:Children's Book Council of Australia, Picture Book of the Year, Winner for Cicada<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.booksandpublishing.com.au/articles/2019/08/16/137855/cbca-awards-2019-winners-announced/|title=CBCA Awards 2019 winners announced|date=2019-08-16|website=Books+Publishing|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n*''The Red Tree'', a play based on Tan's book of the same name, was commissioned by the Queensland Performing Arts Centre.<ref>[http://www.qpac.com.au/media/releases/OOTB_Red_Tree Queensland Performing Arts Centre Media Release] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060819102943/http://www.qpac.com.au/media/releases/OOTB_Red_Tree |date=19 August 2006 }}</ref>\n*''The Red Tree'', a music performance created by new composer [[Michael Yezerski]] with [[Richard Tognetti]]; performed by the [[Australian Chamber Orchestra]] with the youth choir [[Gondwana Voices]], and accompanied by images from the book.<ref name = \"ACO\">[http://www.aco.com.au/?url=/redtree Australian Chamber Orchestra ''The Red Tree''] Accessed: 2008-05-29</ref>\n* ''The Arrival''. Images from this book were projected during a performance by the Australian Chamber Orchestra of conductor Richard Tognetti\u2019s arrangement of Shostakovich\u2019s String Quartet No. 15<ref name = \"ACO\"/>\n* ''The Lost Thing'' has been adapted as an Oscar-winning animated short film.<ref>[http://www.lothian.com.au/AboutAuthors.aspx Lothian Books]</ref>\n* ''The Lost Thing'' inspired an album by Sydney band [[Lo-Tel]], complete with artwork from the book.\n* ''The Lost Thing'' has also been adapted as a play by the Jigsaw Theatre Company,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jigsawtheatre.com.au/ |title=Jigsaw Theatre Company<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=6 November 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070830130621/http://www.jigsawtheatre.com.au/ |archive-date=30 August 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> a youth theatre company in [[Canberra]]. This was the main event for the National Gallery of Australia's Children Festival ([[Canberra]]) and at the Chookahs! Kids Festival ([[Melbourne, Australia|Melbourne]]) in 2006.\n* ''The Lost Thing'' was the theme for the 2006 Chookahs! Kids Festival at The Arts Centre<ref>[http://www.theartscentre.net.au/ Homepage \u2013 The Arts Centre \u2013 the home of the performing arts in Melbourne<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> in [[Melbourne, Australia|Melbourne]], with many different activities based on concepts from the book.\n* ''The Arrival'' was adapted for the stage by Red Leap Theatre.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.australianstage.com.au/201001123106/reviews/sydney-festival/the-arrival-%7c-red-leap-theatre.html |title=The Arrival \u2013 Red Leap Theatre |publisher=Australian Stage |date=12 January 2009 |accessdate=12 January 2009}}</ref>\n*''The Arrival'' was again projected on a screen to an orchestral score, performed by Orkestra of the Underground with 18 pieces created by musician and composer Ben Walsh. This was performed in the Opera House in Sydney, The Melbourne Recital Centre and Her Majesty's Theatre in Adelaide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.benw.info/orkestraoftheunderground/arrival.html | title=Orkestra of the Underground}}</ref>\n*''The Rabbits'' was the basis for an [[opera]] of [[The Rabbits|the same title]] by [[Kate Miller-Heidke]] which was premiered at the 2015 [[Perth International Arts Festival]].\n\n==Works ==\n\n===Books===\n====As illustrator====\n* ''The Pipe'', by James Moloney (1996)\n* ''The Stray Cat'', by [[Steven Paulsen]] (1996)\n* ''The Doll'', by Janine Burke (1997)\n* ''The Half Dead'', by [[Garry Disher]] (1997)\n* ''The Viewer'', written by [[Gary Crew]] (1997)\n* ''The Rabbits'', written by [[John Marsden (writer)|John Marsden]] (1998)\n* ''The Hicksville Horror'', by Nette Hilton (1999)\n* ''The Puppet'', by Ian Bone (1999)\n* ''Memorial'', written by [[Gary Crew]] (1999)\n* ''Pretty Monsters'' by Kelly Link (2008)\n\n====As author and illustrator====\n* ''[[The Playground (book)|The Playground]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[The Lost Thing]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[The Red Tree (Shaun Tan)|The Red Tree]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[The Arrival (graphic novel)|The Arrival]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Tales from Outer Suburbia]]'' (2008)\n* ''The Bird King and other sketches'' (2011)\n* ''The Oopsatoreum: inventions of Henry A. Mintox'', with the [[Powerhouse Museum]] (2012)\n* ''Rules of Summer'' (2013)\n* ''The Singing Bones'' (2016)\n* ''Cicada'' (2018)\n* ''Tales from the Inner City'' (2018)\n\n===Installations===\n*Mural in the Children's Section of the Subiaco Public Library (Perth, Western Australia).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shaun|first1=Tan|title=The Tea Party|url=http://www.shauntan.net/projects.html#anchor%20tea%20party|accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [https://archive.is/20010302070555/http://www.schools.ash.org.au/asspa/Shaun.htm \"About Shaun Tan\" ''Aboriginal Student Support and Parent Awareness Program''] Retrieved 27 December 2005\n* [http://www.lothian.com.au/AboutAuthors.aspx \"About Our Authors and Illustrators\". ''Lothian Books''] Retrieved 27 December 2005\n* [http://www.locusmag.com/2001/Issue12/Tan.html Haber, K. (2001) \"Shaun Tan: Out Of Context\", ''Locus magazine''] Retrieved 27 December 2005\n* [http://www.det.wa.edu.au/media_releases/docs/balcatta.pdf \"Media Statement (2005)\", ''Western Australia Department of Education and Training''] Retrieved 27 December 2005\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060819102943/http://www.qpac.com.au/media/releases/OOTB_Red_Tree \"The Red Tree\", ''Queensland Performing Arts Centre''] Retrieved 27 December 2005\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050616144807/http://www.subiaco.wa.gov.au/cos/events/shauntan.html \"Shaun Tan Award For Young Artists\", ''City of Subiaco''] Retrieved 27 December 2005\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060819001754/http://dreamstone.com.au/artisthtml/shaun_tan.htm \"Shaun Tan: Biography\", ''Dreamstone''] Retrieved 27 December 2005\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050514153021/http://www.unimelb.edu.au/ExtRels/Media/UN/archive/2000/518/shaun.html \"Shaun puts students in the picture (2000)\", ''The University of Melbourne''] Retrieved 27 December 2005\n* [http://www.austlit.edu.au/run?ex=ShowAgent&agentId=A%2C%7D9 \"Tan, Shaun\", ''AustLit''] Retrieved 27 December 2005\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060103115511/http://www.education.tas.gov.au/english/tan2.htm Tan, S. (2001) \"Originality and Creativity\", ''AATE/ALEA Joint National Conference''] Retrieved 27 December 2005\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060103101445/http://www.education.tas.gov.au/english/tan1.htm Tan, S. (2001) \"Picture Books: Who Are They For?\", ''AATE/ALEA Joint National Conference''] Retrieved 27 December 2005\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box|by=yes|onlinebooks=no|about=yes|wikititle=Shaun Tan}}\n{{Commons category|Shaun Tan}}\n*{{official website|http://www.shauntan.net}}\n* {{isfdb name |7201 |Shaun Tan}}\n* {{IMDb name |1316810 |Shaun Tan}}\n*[https://beinart.org/collections/shaun-tan Shaun Tan collection at Beinart Gallery]\n*[http://www.inframe.tv/videoproject.aspx?id=10/ InFrame.tv interview with Shaun Tan on the animated adaptation of his book The Lost Thing]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070831013750/http